Your Digest for Tuesday, Mar 26, 2024 01:59 PM

- **Eearly** loss of *vibration and joint position sense*. 
- Dorsal root (i.e **sensory**) *axonal neuropathy*. 
  **Pain and temperature are preserved**. 
- So, loss of JPS and vibration *exacerbates* the *cerebellar ataxia*. 
- Autonomic nervous system involvement -> bladder dysfunction. 
- **reflexes are eventually lost** in most patients. (but can be preserved in *atypical phenotypes*) 
- Also, dysphagia, *dysarthria*.
- Reduced visual acuity and hearing loss can occur. 
- **Cognition is preserved**.
  • Staggering gait in childhood (due to ataxia of all four limbs) is the main symptom. 4
    • Lower limbs are affected before the upper limbs.

Diagnosis:
Clinical and with detection of expansions of the FXN gene.

X-ray changes in rheumatoid arthritis

Source

  • bilateral and symmetrical involvement
  • proximal interphalangeal joint space narrowing (yellow arrows)
  • metacarpophalangeal joint space narrowing (blue arrows)
  • metacarpal heads erosions (red arrows)
  • metacarpophalangeal joint osteopenia (green circles)
  • pancarpal and radiocarpal involvement with erosions (yellow circles)
  • carpometacarpal erosion (purple arrows)
  • distal radioulnar joint loss of space (black arrows)
  • distal interphalangeal joints spared
  • soft tissue swelling

The presence of leukocytes in the anterior chamber of the eye is characteristic of anterior uveitis.

Radiographic grading of sacroiliac joints.
Grade 1: Suspicious changes, not definitive.
Grade 2: Small localised areas of erosions or sclerosis; normal joint space width.
Grade 3: Definite changes of erosions, sclerosis, narrowing or partial fusion.
Grade 4: Complete fusion
Source
Syndesmophytes and changes of spondylitis in the spine, which are most often detected in more longstanding disease.
A syndesmophyte is a bony growth originating inside a ligament, commonly seen in the ligaments of the spine, specifically the ligaments in the intervertebral joints leading to fusion of vertebrae.
Inflammatory osteoproliferative lesions in the spine are called syndesmophytes (marginal and non-marginal), and degenerative osteoproliferative lesions are called osteophytes. Syndesmophytes are more vertically oriented than osteophytes.

[!INFO] Syndesmophytes are only seen in

  • ankylosing spondylitis
  • ochronosis
  • fluorosis
  • reactive arthritis
  • psoriatic arthritis
    Note: NOT in rheumatoid arthritis.

    Lumbar spine changes in AS. A) Shiny corners and erosions. B) Early syndesmophytes C) Spinal fusion or ankylosis
    Source

CPPD disease can be differentiated from gout on ultrasound given that echogenic monosodium urate crystals line the surface of articular cartilage, whereas echogenic CPPD calcifications are located within the cartilage itself*

[!INFO] Chondrocalcinosis
#chondrocalcinosis #2015MCQ-APR/Q31
Deposition of calcium in the articular cartilates (chondrocalcinosis) is very common in CPPD. (almost so much that it's synonymous). However, it is NOT present in all CPPD and not all chondrocalcinosis is due to CPPD. Therefore, chondrocalcinosis is not diagnostic of CPPD.
